The pelvis is shaped like a fancy cocktail glass. It has a larger, upper bowl (A) and a smaller lower bowl (B). 
The false pelvis is the larger, upper bowl. It borders the lower abdominal wall and contains abdominal organs. The smaller, lower bowl is the true pelvis. It contains pelvic organs. 
The plane that separates the false and true pelvis is the pelvic inlet. The bony features that contribute to the pelvic inlet are labeled in this illustration.
In anatomical position, as in this figure, the ASIS and the pubic tubercles are in the same vertical plane. Therefore, the pelvic inlet is tipped very much forward and the body of the pubis is facing inferiorly, rather than anteriorly.
That’s right! The false pelvis contributes to the abdominal wall.
